In Latin the opposite process took place. Latin, like Greek, had inherited from the beginninga few non-reduplicated per· iects3 in another type, eg. aedi, the reduplication remained, but was no longer perceptible, and we have seen that this type was extended by analogy3 lastly, in the whole of a very important class of socalled perfecte the reduplication was regularly absent, namely in the old sigmatic aorists which became entirely confused with the periect;1 hence there was abundant reason why this element should tend everywhere to fall into disuse. Accordingly the perfecte mentioned above are almost the only reduplicated perfecte in Latin. In all the perfecte in at, ct, and the great bulk of radical perfecte, there is no reduplication, trev-t, lc-v-t, sec-t, otc-t, tol-r (for ic-tal-i); much more is this the case with all the false perfecte iu -st, which never had it, caeci, fibert, pcamt (cf. pepigi, both from paroye). Further, in Latin as in Greek, the perieots which have reduplication keep it in all moods: pre-pendere, pc- pettder-i-m, like lte-hoco, λε-λύκ-οι-μι.
